ounced and contextualized through written communiqués, which are posted online, translated, and circulated globally. This book offers the first contemporary history of these digitally-mediated networks, and seeks to locate this tendency within anti-state struggles from the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnarchismxHistory. 0aRevolutionsxHistory. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aBlanquism.  aCCF.  aInformal Anarchist Federation.  aThe Invisible Committee.  aTiqqun.  aaction-orientated research.  acapitalism.  afeminist methodology identity politics.  aguerrilla warfare.  ainsurrectionary anarchists.  anihilist-infused anarchism.  aonline communiqués.  aoppressive powers.  apolitical violence.  asecuritization.  astandpoint theory.  astructural violence.  aterrorism.  aunderground networks.  awar-like conditions.1 aLoadenthal, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612813340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526128133423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526128133/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles